ntury Spanish musicians]]\n[[Category:Andalusian musicians]]\n[[Category:Ballet composers]]\n[[Category:Burials in Spain]]\n[[Category:Composers for piano]]\n[[Category:Exiles of the Spanish Civil War in Argentina]]\n[[Category:Flamenco musicians]]\n[[Category:Madrid Royal Conservatory alumni]]\n[[Category:Male classical pianists]]\n[[Category:Male opera composers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Royal Academy of Belgium]]\n[[Category:People from C\u00e1diz]]\n[[Category:Spanish classical composers]]\n[[Category:Spanish classical pianists]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriates in France]]\n[[Category:Spanish male classical composers]]\n[[Category:Spanish opera composers]]\n", "name_user": "Thoughtfortheday", "label": "safe", "comment": "sub-category", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manuel_de_Falla"}
{"title_page": "Onome Ebi", "text_new": "{{short description|Nigerian football defender|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Onome Ebi\n| fullname = Onome Ebi<ref name=\"FIFA 2015\">{{cite news |url=http://www.fifadata.com/document/FWWC/2015/pdf/FWWC_2015_SquadLists.pdf |title=List of Players \u2013 2015 FIFA Women's World Cup |work=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] |accessdate=20 June 2015 |format=PDF}}</ref>\n| image = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1983|5|8}}<ref name=\"FIFA 2015\"/>\n| birth_place = [[Lagos]], [[Nigeria]]\n| currentclub = [[Henan Huishang F.C.|Henan Huishang]]\n| clubnumber = 25\n| height = 1.75 m<ref name=\"FIFA 2015\"/>\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| years1 = 2001\u20132008\n| clubs1 = Omidiran Babes\n| caps1 = \n| goals1 = \n| years2 = 2008\n| clubs2 = [[Bayelsa Queens]]\n| caps2 = \n| goals2 = \n| years3 = 2009\n| clubs3 = [[Pite\u00e5 IF ladies team|Pite\u00e5]]\n| caps3 = 6\n| goals3 = 1\n| years4 = 2010\n| clubs4 = [[Djurg\u00e5rdens IF Dam|Djurg\u00e5rden]]\n| caps4 = 16\n| goals4 = 0\n| years5 = 2010\u20132011\n| clubs5 = [[D\u00fcvenciler Lisesispor]]\n| caps5 = 7\n| goals5 = 5\n| years6 = 2011\u20132013\n| clubs6 = [[Ata\u015fehir Belediyespor]]\n| caps6 = 28\n| goals6 = 21\n| years7 = 2013\n| clubs7 = [[Sunnan\u00e5 SK]]\n| caps7 = 8\n| goals7 = 0\n| years8 = 2014\u20132017\n| clubs8 = [[FC Minsk (women)|FC Minsk]]\n| caps8 = 9\n| goals8 = 1\n| years9 = 2018\u2013\n| clubs9 = [[Henan Huishang F.C.|Henan Huishang]]\n| caps9 = \n| goals9 = \n| nationalteam1 = [[Nigeria women's national football team|Nigeria]]\n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalcaps1 = 81<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/players/player=190157/index.html |title=Profile |publisher=FIFA.com |accessdate=20 April 2019}}</ref>\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| pcupdate = 20:02, 29 June 2015 (UTC)\n| ntupdate = 15:58, 17 June 2015 (UTC)\n}}\n\n'''Onome Ebi''' is a [[Nigeria]]n [[women's soccer|football]] [[defender (association football)|defender]] currently playing for [[Henan Huishang F.C.|Henan Huishang]] in the [[Chinese Women's Super League]] and the [[Nigeria women's national football team|Nigerian national team]], Super Falcons. In 2019 she became the first African footballer to play in 5 FIFA World Cup Tournaments.\n\n==Club career==\nShe played for [[Bayelsa Queens|Bayelsa Queens FC]] in the [[Nigerian Women's Championship]] before moving to [[Pite\u00e5 IF]] and [[Djurg\u00e5rdens IF Fotboll (women)|Djurg\u00e5rdens IF]] in [[Sweden]]'s [[Damallsvenskan]]. Ebi said \"I enjoyed my stay in Turkey because of the good weather. Going to Sweden was a different ball game, as the cold weather made it difficult for me to play good football. The amateur nature of the Swedish league made me launch a return to Turkey for Ata\u015fehir Belediyespor FC in the First League.\"<ref name=\"newtelegraph\">{{cite news |last1=Sotuminu |first1=Dapo |title=Onome Ebi: No Regrets Dropping Out Of School To Play Soccer |url=https://newtelegraphonline.com/onome-ebi-no-regrets-dropping-school-play-soccer/ |accessdate=10 November 2016 |work=New Telegraph |date=24 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe then played for [[Turkey|Turkish]] sides [[D\u00fcvenciler Lisesispor]] and [[Ata\u015fehir Belediyespor]] at the [[Turkish Women's First Football League|First League]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nwani |first1=Emeka |title=Super Falcons' Onome Ebi wins Turkish league title |url=http://www.goal.com/en-ng/news/4093/nigeria/2012/06/14/3174534/super-falcons-onome-ebi-wins-turkish-league-title |publisher=Goal.com |accessdate=10 November 2016 |date=14 June 2012}}</ref> She made her [[UEFA Women's Champions League|Champions League]] debut in [[2012-13 UEFA Women's Champions League|August 2012]] while playing for Ata\u015fehir Belediyespor.<ref>{{cite web |title=Onome Ebi |url=http://www.uefa.com/teamsandplayers/players/player=250031287/profile/index.html |publisher=UEFA |accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe returned to the Swedish Damallsvenskan in 2013 to play for [[Sunnan\u00e5 SK]] before going to [[Belarus]] to play for [[FC Minsk (women)|FC Minsk]] in the [[Belarusian Premier League (women)|Belarusian Premier League]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.goal.com/en-ng/news/4110/nigerians-abroad/2015/04/18/10879022/nigerian-trio-help-fk-minsk-win-belarus-women-super-cup |title=Nigerian trio help FK Minsk win Belarus Women Super Cup |publisher=Goal.com |accessdate=29 June 2015}}</ref> While there, she was a member of the team that won the [[Belarusian Premier League (women)|Belarusian Premier League]], the [[Belarusian Women's Cup]] and the [[Belarusian Women's Super Cup]] twice.<ref name=\"newtelegraph\"/>\n\nIn both club and international competitions, Ebi plays as the number five in the team due to the significance it holds for her. When she arrived at Minsk, the jersey number was already taken, so she asked for the number 55 instead.<ref name=\"newtelegraph\"/>\n\nShe currently plays for Chinese second division side Henan Huishang, where she signed in 2018.\n\n==International career==\nEbi is a member of the [[Nigeria women's national football team|Nigerian national team]]. On 6 July 2019, she became the first African Footballer to play in five<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/nigerias-onome-ebi-makes-african-history-with-fifth-womens-world-/1ufj402t0guw91uzvkl7kvrkft|title=Nigeria's Onome Ebi makes African history with fifth Women's World Cup appearance {{!}} Goal.com|last=Correspondent|website=www.goal.com|language=en|access-date=2019-06-13}}</ref> [[FIFA Women's World Cup|Fifa World Cup]] Tournaments, taking part in the [[2003 FIFA Women's World Cup|2003]], [[2007 FIFA Women's World Cup|2007]], [[2011 FIFA Women's World Cup|2011]] and [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup|2015]], [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup|2019]] editions of the [[FIFA Women's World Cup]] and the [[Football at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|2008 Beijing Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/statisticsandrecords/players/player=190157/ |title=FIFA player stats |publisher=FIFA |accessdate=29 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Saaid |first1=Hamdan |title=Games of the XXIX. Olympiad |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tableso/ol2008f-women-det.html |publisher=RSSSF |accessdate=10 November 2016 |date=18 September 2008}}</ref>\n\nEbi was also a member of the Nigerian squad in the [[2008 African Women's Championship|2008]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Nigeria/Ghana: 2008 African Women Championship \u2013 Super Falcons Begin Campaign Against Ghana Today |url=http://allafrica.com/stories/200811180993.html |accessdate=10 November 2016 |work=AllAfrica |date=11 November 2008}}</ref> [[2010 African Women's Championship|2010]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Falcons go headlong for women\u2019s title on SuperSport |url=http://www.bloemfonteincelticfc.co.za/articles.aspx?Id=382040 |publisher=Bloemfontein Celtic |accessdate=10 November 2016 |date=28 October 2010}}</ref> [[2012 African Women's Championship|2012]], [[2014 African Women's Championship|2014]], [[2016 African Women's Championship|2016]] and [[2018 Africa Women Cup of Nations|2018]] editions of the [[African Women's Championship]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Falcons\u2019 Onome Ebi joins other pros in camp |url=http://m.news24.com.ng/nigeria/Sport/Football/Falcons-Onome-Ebi-joins-other-pros-in-camp-20121016 |accessdate=10 November 2016 |work=News 24 |date=16 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Ahmadu |first1=Samuel |title=Minsk Release Esther Sunday & Onome Ebi for AWC |url=http://www.goal.com/en-ng/news/4093/nigerian-football/2014/09/29/5142661/minsk-release-esther-sunday-onome-ebi-for-awc |publisher=Goal.com |accessdate=10 November 2016 |date=29 September 2014}}</ref> winning the tournament four times [[2010 African Women's Championship|2010]], [[2014 African Women's Championship|2014]]) [[2016 African Women's Championship|2016]] and [[2018 Africa Women Cup of Nations|2018]] .<ref>{{cite news |title=African International Competitions |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/9049468.stm |accessdate=10 November 2016 |work=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Nigeria reclaim African women's title |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/29739296 |accessdate=10 November 2016 |work=BBC Sport |date=25 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Club===\n; Ata\u015fehir Belediyespor\n* [[Turkish Women's First Football League]] (2): 2011\u201312, 2012\u201313\n\n; FC Minsk\n* [[Belarusian Premier League (women)|Belarusian Premier League]] (1): [[2014 Belarusian Premier League (women)|2014]]\n* [[Belarusian Women's Cup]] (1): 2014\n* [[Belarusian Women's Super Cup]] (2): 2014, 2015\n\n===International===\n; Nigeria\n* [[African Women's Championship]] (4): [[2010 African Women's Championship|2010]], [[2014 African Women's Championship|2014]], [[2016 African Women's Championship|2016]],[[2018 Africa Women Cup of Nations|2018]]\n\nFourth Place: [[2012 African Women's Championship|2012]]\n\n'''Individual Awards'''\n\n* NFF-Aiteo Female Player Of The Year: 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-ng/news/onome-ebi-wins-2018-nff-womens-player-of-the-year-award/16izczr91zruh126hu8nb7kf7j|title=Onome Ebi wins 2018 NFF Women's Player of the Year award {{!}} Goal.com|last=Correspondent|website=www.goal.com|language=en|access-date=2019-06-13}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{FIFA player|190157}}\n* {{UEFA player|250031287}}\n* {{Svenskfotboll|pid=6502|fid=616858}}\n* {{Soccerway|onome-ebi/19449}}\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n| title = Nigeria squads\n| bg = #008751\n| fg = white\n| list1 = \n{{Nigeria squad 2003 FIFA Women's World Cup}}\n{{Nigeria squad 2007 FIFA Women's World Cup}}\n{{Nigeria women's football squad 2008 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Nigeria squad 2008 African Women's Championship}}\n{{Nigeria squad 2010 African Women's