ury Nigerian actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Delta State]]\n[[Category:Best of Nollywood Awards winners]]\n[[Category:University of Benin (Nigeria) alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Benin City]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues| \n{{third-party|date=April 2017}}\n{{BLP sources|date=August 2016}}\n{{COI|date=August 2016}}\n}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Omoni Oboli\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1978|4|22|df=yes}}<ref name=\"iroko\">{{cite web | url=http://irokotv.com/actor/494/omoni-oboli | title=Omoni Oboli | publisher=[[Irokotv]] | accessdate=14 October 2015}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Benin City]], [[Edo State|Edo]], Nigeria<ref name=\"iroko\" />\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Nnamdi Oboli|2000}}<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.pulse.ng/entertainment/celebrities/omoni-oboli-actress-on-how-shes-still-married-17-years-later-id7008903.html? |title= Omoni Oboli: Actress on how she's still married 17 years later |date= 18 July 2017 |publisher= [[pulse.ng]] |accessdate= 24 December 2017}}</ref>\n| children           = Gozi oboli\nChizi oboli\nTobe oboli\n| nationality        = Nigerian\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Actress, scriptwriter, director, [[Film producer|producer]]<ref name=\"source1\">{{cite news|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/200909090465.html?viewall=1|title=Nigeria: Sexual Harassment Not Peculiar to Nollywood -Omoni|last=Medeme|first=Ovwe|date=9 September 2009|work=[[AllAfrica.com]]|publisher=[[AllAfrica Global Media]]|accessdate=11 March 2011}}</ref>\n| known_for          = \n| yearsactive        = 1996; 2009 \u2014 present\n}}\n'''Omoni Oboli''' (born 22 April 1978) is a Nigerian actress, scriptwriter, film director, producer and a trained digital filmmaker. She studied at the [[New York Film Academy]], and has written several screenplays such as; [[The Figurine|The figurine]] (2009), Anchor baby(2010), ''Fatal Imagination'', ''Being Mrs Elliott'', ''The First Lady'', and ''[[Wives on Strike]](2016)''.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nOboli was born in [[Benin City]], [[Edo State]]. She is a descendant of Mosogar in [[Delta State]].<ref name=\"iroko\" /> Omoni Oboli studied [[Foreign language|Foreign Languages]] (majoring in French) at the [[University of Benin (Nigeria)|University of Benin]], and graduated with honours (2nd Class Upper division).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://amp-pulse-ng.cdn.ampproject.org/v/s/amp.pulse.ng/entertainment/celebrities/award-winning-multi-talented-actress-omoni-oboli-id8603015.html?amp_js_v=a2&amp_gsa=1&usqp=mq331AQCCAE=#referrer=https://www.google.com&amp_tf=From%20%251$s&ampshare=https://www.pulse.ng/entertainment/celebrities/award-winning-multi-talented-actress-omoni-oboli-id8603015.html|title=Award-winning, multi-talented actress, Omoni Oboli|website=amp-pulse-ng.cdn.ampproject.org|language=en-UK|access-date=2018-07-26}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nOmoni began her movie career with her first movie role in ''Bitter Encounter'' (1996), where she played a secretary. Her next was ''Shame''. She then went on to play the lead female character in three major movies; ''Not My Will'', ''Destined To Die'' and ''Another Campus Tale''. After enjoying a brief career in 1996, Omoni left the movie industry to complete her university education. She married immediately after school and did not return to the industry until a decade later.\n\nOmoni has several screenplays to her credit, including her film ''Wives On Strike'' as well as ''The Rivals'', a movie she co-produced with her friend and won the prize for Best International Drama at the New York International Independent Film & Video Festival.<ref name=\":0\" /> It was the first Nigerian film to be premiered since the festival\u2019s inception in 2003.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}} The movie was given a 3-star rating out of 4 by the festival's judges.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\nOmoni has played lead roles in mainstream films, including: ''[[The Figurine]]'' (2009), ''[[Anchor Baby]]'' (2010), ''[[Being Mrs Elliot]]'', and ''[[Fifty]]'' (2015). She is also the first actress from Nollywood to win Best Actress in two international festivals,{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}} (that are not organized by Nigerians or Africans), in the same year (2010). This she did at the Harlem International Film Festival and the Los Angeles Movie Awards for her lead role in the movie ''Anchor Baby''.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\n== Awards and Nominations ==\nIn 2010, she won the award for Best Actress Narrative Feature at the Los Angeles Movie Awards, and the award for Best Actress at the [[Harlem International Film Festival]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}} Omoni was nominated for the Best Actress in a leading role award at the 2011 [[Africa Movie Academy Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gabzinc.com/2011/03/the-2011-africa-movie-academy-awards-nominees-list/|title=The 2011 Africa Movie Academy Awards Nominees List {{!}} ::GABz Incorporated::|website=gabzinc.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-11-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, she won Big Screen Actress of the Year award, at the 2014 ELOY Awards, for her movie ''Being Mrs Elliott''. In 2015, Omoni was awarded the Sun Nollywood \"Personality of the Year\",<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.playground.ng/2015/12/the-sun-nollywood-personality-of-the-year-2015-award-is-honour-money-cant-buy-actress-omoni-oboli/|title=The ''Sun Nollywood Personality'' of the Year 2015 Award is an Honour money cannot buy \u2013 Actress, Omoni Oboli - Playground.ng|date=2015-12-11|work=Playground.ng|access-date=2017-11-29|language=en-GB}}</ref> She has directed several movies such as ''Being Mrs Elliott'', ''The First Lady'', ''Wives on Strike'', and ''[[Okafor's Law]]''.\n\nOn the 14th of August 2017, Omoni Oboli took to her [[instagram]] page to share a post announcing her new deal as the [[Brand ambassador]] of [[Olawale Ayilara]]'s LandWey Investment Limited.<ref name=\"bellaomoni\">{{cite web |title=Omoni Oboli becomes Landwey Investment Brand Ambassador |url=https://www.bellanaija.com/2017/08/omoni-oboli-landwey-investment-ambassador/amp/ |publisher=Bella Naija |accessdate=5 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Legal issue ==\nOmoni Oboli starred in the movie ''[[Okafor's Law]],'' which premiered on 24 March 2017. However, the movie could not be screened at the premiere due to an [[injunction]] by the court. Oboli was accused of [[copyright infringement]] by [[Jude Idada]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thenet.ng/2017/03/omoni-oboli-vs-jude-idada-nigerians-react-okafors-law-theft-saga-premiere-cancellation/|title=Omoni Oboli vs. Jude Idada: Nigerians react to 'Okafor\u2019s Law' theft saga, premiere cancellation|date=2017-03-25|work=Nigerian Entertainment Today|access-date=2017-04-14|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://pulse.ng/movies/okafors-law-jude-idada-says-omoni-oboli-stole-movie-from-him-id5466984.html|title=\"Okafor\"s Law\": Jude Idada says Omoni Oboli stole movie from him|last=Izuzu|first=Chidumga|access-date=2017-05-08|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://silverbirdtv.com/entertainment/15123-court-adjourns-case-between-omoni-oboli-and-jude-idada|title=Court Adjourns Case Between Omoni Oboli and Jude Idada {{!}} Silverbird Television|website=silverbirdtv.com|language=en|access-date=2017-05-08}}</ref> who claimed to have written part of the script for ''Okafor's Law''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tns.ng/audio-jude-idada-accuses-omoni-oboli-stealing-okafors-law/|title=TNS Exclusive: (AUDIO) Jude Idada Accuses Omoni Oboli Of \u2018Stealing\u2019 \"Okafor\u2019s Law\"|date=2017-03-27|work=TNS|access-date=2017-05-08|language=en-GB}}</ref> The movie was released on 31 March 2017.<ref>[https://tns.ng/omoni-oboli-tears-okafors-law-premiere-fails-hold/ \"Video: 'My Story, My Script, My Film!'\u2013 Omoni Oboli Insists As 'Okafor\u2019s Law' Premiere Is Cancelled\"], TNS, 24 March 2017.</ref>\n\n== Charity ==\nOmoni Oboli set up a charity organization, \"The Omoni Oboli Foundation\" to use her celebrity status to bring well-needed relief to the plight of the less privileged women and children of Nigerian society. The foundation has been able to embark on several projects which include the following:\n* The feeding of street children in Lagos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ngr.ng/actress-omoni-oboli-takes-her-40th-birthday-to-the-streets-feeds-1200-kids-in-lagos-photos/|title=Actress, Omoni Oboli Takes Her 40th Birthday To The Streets, Feeds 1,200 Kids In Lagos (Photos) - Naija news Naij news|last=Rucky|website=ngr.ng|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-26}}</ref>\n* Feeding and giving over two hundred poor and disadvantaged children at Delta Steel Complex, Aladja, a fun day with practical gifts.\n* Broadening the mindset of the less privileged children by taking the children of Ecole Divine Nursery Primary and Secondary School to a milk factory to see how it is made and packaged.\n\n== Filmography ==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%;\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" background: #f9f9f0;\n|- align=\"center\"\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Film\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Role\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Notes\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2009\n| ''Entanglement''\n|\n|  with [[Desmond Elliot]], Mercy Johnson & Yemi Blaq\n|-\n| ''[[The Figurine]]''\n|Mona\n|  with [[Ramsey Nouah]] & Kunle Afolayan\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2010\n|''Bent Arrows''\n|Lola\n| with [[Olu Jacobs]], [[Joke Silva]], [[Stella Damasus-Aboderin]] & [[Desmond Elliot]]\n|-\n| ''[[Anchor Baby (film)|Anchor Baby]]''\n| Joyce Unanga\n| with [[Sam Sarpong]]\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Feathered Dreams]]''\n| Sade\n| with Andrew Rozhen, Philippa Peter-Kubor\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 2014\n| ''[[Brother's Keeper (2014 film)|Brother's Keeper]]''\n| Mena\n| with [[Majid Michel]]\n|-\n| ''[[Render to Caesar]]''\n| Alero\n| with [[Gbenga Akinnagbe]]\n|-\n| ''[[Being Mrs Elliot]]''\n|\n| with [[Majid Michel]], [[Ayo Makun|AY]] & [[Uru Eke]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" | 2015\n| ''[[Lunch Time Heroes]]''\n| Governor's wife\n| with [[Dakore Akande]]\n|-\n| ''[[The Duplex (film)|The Duplex]]''\n| Adaku\n| with [[Mike Ezuruonye]]\n|-\n| ''[[As Crazy as it Gets]]''\n| Katherine\n|\n|-\n|''The First Lady''\n|Michelle\n|with Alexx Ekubo, Yvonne Jegede, Chinedu Ikedieze & Joseph Benjamin\n|-\n| ''[[Fifty (film)|Fifty]]''\n| Maria\n| with [[Ireti Doyle]], [[Nse Ikpe Etim]] and [[Dakore Akande]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2016\n|''Wives on Strike''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bellanaija.com/2016/02/watch-the-trailer-for-wives-on-strike-starring-uche-jombo-omoni-oboli-ufuoma-mcdermott-more/|title=Watch the Trailer for \"Wives On Strike\" starring Uche Jombo, Omoni Oboli, Ufuoma McDermott & More|website=BellaNaija|access-date=2016-05-12}}</ref>\n|\n|with [[Chioma Chukwuka]]''', [[Uche Jombo]], [[Kalu Ikeagwu]]'''\n|-\n|''[[Okafor's Law]]''\n|Ejiro \n| with [[Blossom Chukwujekwu]], [[Gabriel Afolayan]], [[Ufuoma McDermott]]\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[The Wedding Party 2]]''\n|\n|with [[Adesua Etomi]], [[Banky W]]ellington, [[Chiwetalu Agu]], [[Patience Ozokwor]]\n|-\n|2017\n|''Wives on Strike 2''\n|\n|with [[Chioma Chukwuka]]''', [[Uche Jombo]], [[Ufuoma McDermott]] [[Toyin Abraham]]'''\n|-\n|2017\n|''My Wife and I''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pulse.ng/entertainment/movies/pulse-movie-review-my-wife-and-i-is-refreshingly-funny-and-entertaining/73gk11k|title=\"My Wife and I\" is refreshingly funny and entertaining|date=2017-08-15|website=www.pulse.ng|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-22}}</ref>\n|\n|with [[Ramsey Nouah]]\n|-\n|2018\n|''Moms at War''\n|\n|with [[Funke Akindele]]\n|-\n|2019\n|[[Sugar Rush (2019 film)|''Sugar Rush'']]\n|\n|\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{cite web |url=https://okhit.net/actresss-omoni-oboli-returns-back-to-school/ |title='Actresss Omoni Oboli Returns Back To School |publisher=OkHit Media}}\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|id=3905465|name=Omoni Oboli}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oboli, Omoni}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Nigerian actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Delta State]]\n[[Category:Best of Nollywood Awards winners]]\n[[Category:University of Benin (Nigeria) alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Benin City]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAwards and Nominations:Datefixes, replaced: the 14th of August 2017 \u2192 14 August 2017", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Omoni_Oboli"}
{"title_page": "Jimmy Davis (footballer)", "text_new": "{{Other people|James Davis}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|           name = Jimmy Davis\n|          image = \n|        caption = \n|       fullname = James Roger William Davis<ref name=\"hugman\">{{Hugman|4851|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n|     birth_date = {{birth date|1982|2|6|df=y}}<ref name=\"hugman\"/>\n|    birth_place = [[Bromsgrove]], England<ref name=\"bromsgrove\">{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=164 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/164/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n|     death_date = {{death date and age|2003|8|9|1982|2|6|df=y}}\n|    death_place = [[Oxfordshire]], England\n|         height = {{height|m=1.73}}<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/><ref name=\"soccerbase\">{{cite web|url=https://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=23849 |url-status=live |title=Jimmy Davis |work=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm Ltd |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n|       position = [[Midfielder#Winger|Winger]]<ref name=\"hugman\"/><br/>[[Forward (association football)|Forward]]<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/>\n|    youthyears1 = 1998\u20131999 |youthclubs1 = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]\n|         years1 = 1999\u20132003 |clubs1 = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]  |caps1 = 0  |goals1 = 0\n|         years2 = 2001      |clubs2 = \u2192 [[Royal Antwerp F.C.|Royal Antwerp]] (loan) |caps2 = 7  |goals2 = 0\n|         years3 = 2002      |clubs3 = \u2192 [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] (loan)   |caps3 = 13 |goals3 = 2\n|         years4 = 2003      |clubs4 = \u2192 [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] (loan)             |caps4 = 0  |goals4 = 0\n|      totalcaps = 20        | totalgoals = 2\n| nationalyears1 = 1999      | nationalteam1 = [[England national under-16 football team|England U16]] | nationalcaps1 = 1 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2000      | nationalteam2 = [[England national under-18 football team|England U18]] | nationalcaps2 = 1 | nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2001\u20132002 | nationalteam3 = [[England national under-20 football team|England U20]] | nationalcaps3 = 7 | nationalgoals3 = 3\n}}\n'''James Roger William Davis''' (6 February 1982 \u2013 9 August 2003) was a [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]]. He signed for [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] as a youth trainee in July 1999 and the following month he signed professional terms with the club. He played numerous times for the youth and [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy|reserve]] sides at United and was part of the team that won the [[Manchester Senior Cup]] in  May 2000. He had a short spell on [[Loan (sports)|loan]] at Belgian club [[Royal Antwerp F.C.|Royal Antwerp]] in 2001 before returning to United and making his senior debut in the [[EFL Cup|League Cup]] tie against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] during the [[2001\u201302 Manchester United F.C. season|2001\u201302 season]]. He was an England youth international as he progressed from the [[England national under-16 football team|under-16s]] to the [[England national under-20 football team|under-20s]] during his time at [[Old Trafford]].\n\nDavis spent three months on loan with [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] club [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] in 2002 and scored three goals in 15 appearances. He was a mainstay in the reserves on his return to United; his only involvement with the first team after returning was as an unused [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in a league game against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]  and a [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] second group stage match against [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a]]. In July 2003, he joined [[Football League First Division|First Division]] club [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] on season-long loan. \n\nDavis was killed on the morning on 9 August 2003 when his car was in a collision with a [[Truck|lorry]] whilst travelling southbound on the [[M40 motorway|M40]] in [[Oxfordshire]]. He was due to make his debut for Watford against [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] that afternoon. An [[Inquests in England and Wales|inquest]] determined he was travelling at around 120mph at the time of the incident, and was twice the legal [[Driving under the influence#United Kingdom|drink-drive limit]].<ref name=\"inquest\"/>\n\n==Early life==\nDavis was born in [[Bromsgrove]], Worcestershire.<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/> He lived in [[Redditch]] and attended Marlfield Farm First School<ref name=\"earlyyears\">{{cite web|url=http://www.angelfire.com/pro/jimmydavis/Earlyyears.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040913183908/http://www.angelfire.com/pro/jimmydavis/Earlyyears.html |archivedate=13 September 2004 |title=Jimmy Davis \u2212 Early Years |publisher=Jimmy Davis Memorial Website |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> and later [[RSA Academy Arrow Vale|Arrow Vale High School]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/hereford/worcs/3170367.stm |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416083640/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/hereford/worcs/3170367.stm |archivedate=16 April 2016 |title=Football stars united in grief |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=21 August 2003 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> He played football from an early age, firstly with a [[Cub Scout#United Kingdom|Cub's]] team, and then with junior sides of local clubs [[Feckenham F.C.|Feckenham]] and [[Knowle F.C.|Knowle]].<ref name=\"earlyyears\"/>\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Manchester United===\nDavis signed as a youth trainee at [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in July 1999.<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/> He played in the Jersey Tournament in August 1999; he took part in the win versus [[Rangers F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Rangers]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=186 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/186/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> and the defeat against [[S.L. Benfica Juniors|Benfica]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=187 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/187/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> At the end of August he signed a professional contract with United.<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/> On 25 September, Davis scored a [[Hat-trick#Association football|hat-trick]] in the [[Premier Academy League|FA Premier Academy League]] under-19 match against [[Stoke City F.C. Under-23s and Academy|Stoke City]].<ref name=\"redstat\">{{cite web|url=http://www.redstat.co.uk/?PlayerNo=393 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/mCDBU |archivedate=20 April 2020 |title=Jimmy Davis |work=redStat.co.uk |publisher=redStat \u2212 Manchester United Statistics |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> United won the game 5\u22120.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> He played in the 2\u22121 defeat against [[Nottingham Forest F.C. Under-23s, Under-18s and Academy|Nottingham Forest]] in the [[FA Youth Cup]] third round at [[Gigg Lane]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=197 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/197/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> He started to feature for the [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy|reserves]] more regularly at the beginning on 2000,<ref name=\"redstat\"/> and he scored in the [[Premier Reserve League]] match against [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] in February.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=174 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/174/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> On 2 May, he played in the [[Manchester Senior Cup]] final at [[Boundary Park]]; he replaced [[Darren Fletcher]] as United won 2\u22120 against [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=177 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/177/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nDavis featured in the [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] Centenary Youth Tournament in August 2000; he played in four games and scored against [[FC Bayern Munich Junior Team|Bayern Munich]] and [[FC Spartak Moscow|Spartak Moscow]].<ref name=\"redstat\"/> On 28 September, he scored as United beat [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] 8\u22121 in the Manchester Senior Cup.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> His next goal came in the return game with Bury at the end of November.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> He concluded his season by taking part in a second successive Manchester Senior Cup final.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> He started the game against [[Manchester City F.C. EDS and Academy|Manchester City]] but United lost 4\u22121 at [[Old Trafford]].<ref name=\"redstat\"/>\n\n====Royal Antwerp (loan)====\nIn January 2001, Davis joined [[Belgian First Division A|Belgian Pro League]] club [[Royal Antwerp F.C.|Royal Antwerp]] on loan until the end of the season.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> United had a relationship with Antwerp at the time that would see young players being loaned to Belgian club to gain first team experience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mufclatest.com/whatever-happened-to-royal-antwerp-the-feeder-club-conundrum/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190918180653/http://mufclatest.com/whatever-happened-to-royal-antwerp-the-feeder-club-conundrum/ |archivedate=18 September 2019 |title=Whatever happened to Royal Antwerp? The feeder club conundrum |first=Andrew |last=Bruce |publisher=MUFC Latest |date=1 June 2018 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> However, he only made seven appearances for Antwerp and didn't manage to score any goals.<ref name=\"redstat\"/>\n\nDavis made a positive start to the [[2001\u201302 Manchester United F.C. season|2001\u201302 season]]; he scored a hat-trick for the reserves against [[Newcastle Town F.C.|Newcastle Town]] at the end of September 2001, and then scored two more against [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C. Academy|Sheffield Wednesday]] on 1 November.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> Four days later, he made his senior debut in the [[EFL Cup|League Cup]] tie against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] at [[Arsenal Stadium|Highbury]].<ref name=\"redstat\"/><ref name=\"debutarse\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/worthington_cup/1637817.stm |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306220908/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/worthington_cup/1637817.stm |archivedate=6 March 2016 |title=Arsenal win battle of reserves |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=5 November 2001 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> He played the full game but United lost the [[2001\u201302 Football League Cup#Third round|third round]] match 4\u20130.<ref name=\"debutarse\"/>\n\nDavis was loaned to [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon]] for three months in the [[2002\u201303 in English football|2002\u201303]] season, making 15 appearances for the [[Football League Second Division|Division Two]] side, scoring three goals, although it was not enough to bring anything better than a mid-table finish for [[Andy King (footballer, born 1956)|Andy King's]] side. Davis was keen to accept an offer to extend his deal, but United manager [[Alex Ferguson]] recalled him in November 2002. His last game for Swindon Town was on 9 November. After returning to Old Trafford, he was on the bench for United's Premier League match away to [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] on 17 November,<ref>{{cite news |title=Defoe denies Man Utd |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/2430783.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=17 November 2002 |accessdate=20 April 2020 }}</ref> and was again an unused substitute in their [[UEFA Champions League]] second group stage match away to [[Deportivo La Coruna]] on 18 March 2003.<ref>{{cite news |title=Deportivo see off Man Utd |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/champions_league/2856429.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=18 March 2003 |accessdate=20 April 2020 }}</ref> He joined [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] on a season-long loan on 8 July 2003.<ref>{{cite news |title=Watford lure Man Utd fledgling |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/watford/3054232.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=8 July 2003 |accessdate=20 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===Under-16===\nDavis represented [[England national under-16 football team|England]] at the [[1999 UEFA European Under-16 Championship]]. On 2 May 1999, he featured in the quarter final defeat against host nation [[Czech Republic national under-17 football team|Czech Republic]]; he replaced [[Jamie McMaster]] in the 86th minute as England lost 1\u22120 [[Overtime (sports)#Association football|after extra time]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nv.fotbal.cz/en-national-teams/national-team-u-16/statistics/viewstat2.asp?page=/nat/16/1998/match15.asp |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180722011401/http://nv.fotbal.cz/en-national-teams/national-team-u-16/statistics/viewstat2.asp?page=/nat/16/1998/match15.asp |archivedate=22 July 2018 |title=Z\u00e1pis o utk\u00e1n\u00ed \u010d. 86 |work=Fotbal.cz |publisher=Fotbalov\u00e9 asociace \u010cesk\u00e9 republiky |language=Czech |date=2 May 1999 |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Under-18===\nDavis played for the [[England national under-18 football team|England under-18s]] in the win against [[Belgium national under-18 football team|Belgium]] in November 2000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/5407330.defoe-given-half-a-game/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420123850/https://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/5407330.defoe-given-half-a-game/ |archivedate=20 April 2020 |title=Defoe given half a game |first= |last= |work=Dorset Echo |publisher=Newsquest Media Group Ltd |date=18 November 2000 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Under-20===\nDavis made his debut for the [[England national under-20 football team|England under-20s]] in November 2001; he started the win against [[Portugal national under-20 football team|Portugal]] at [[St Mary's Stadium]] before being replaced by [[Andrew Johnson (footballer, born 1981)|Andrew Johnson]].<ref name=\"engonline\">{{cite web|url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/MatchRsl/MatchRslTmU20.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229151245/http://www.englandfootballonline.com/MatchRsl/MatchRslTmU20.html |archivedate=29 February 2020 |title=England's Matches the under 20's |work=EnglandFootballOnline.com |publisher=England Football Online \u2212 Chris Goodwin & Glen Isherwood |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> On 13 March 2002, he scored two goals in the win against [[Finland national under-20 football team|Finland]] at the [[University of Bolton Stadium|Reebok Stadium]].<ref name=\"engonline\"/> He was a part of the squad that participated in the [[Toulon Tournament]] in May 2002;<ref name=\"espoirs\">{{cite web|url=https://festival-foot-espoirs.com/festival/archives/palmares.php?annee=2002 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914203846/https://festival-foot-espoirs.com/festival/archives/palmares.php?annee=2002 |archivedate=14 September 2019 |title=30\u00c8 Festival International Espoirs |work=Festival-Foot-Espoirs.com |publisher=Festival International Espoirs |language=French |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> he featured in four games, scoring the winning goal in the group game against Portugal,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/U20s/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2002/05/11456.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040313204835/http://www.thefa.com:80/England/U20s/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2002/05/11456.htm |archivedate=13 March 2004 |title=Toulon: Davis on cue to seal victory |first=Lawrie |last=Madden |work=TheFA.com |publisher=The Football Association |date=13 May 2002 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> as England finished in fourth place.<ref name=\"engonline\"/><ref name=\"espoirs\"/> He received the \"Le joueur le + courtois\" award, translated as being the most courteous player in the tournament.<ref name=\"espoirs\"/> These were his last appearances for the U20s. Overall, Davis earned seven caps and scored three goals.<ref name=\"engonline\"/>\n\n==Death==\nDavis was killed in a car crash on the [[M40 motorway]] in the early hours of 9 August 2003. He crashed his [[BMW]] into a truck and was pronounced dead at the scene. The truck driver suffered minor injuries. The accident occurred just hours before Watford were due to open their season with a match against [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]]. The Watford board of directors announced later that morning that the match was postponed due to \"tragic circumstances beyond their control\", though they did not announce Davis' death for another few hours. His funeral took place at Redditch Crematorium, with the Manchester United team in attendance.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,30100-12740453,00.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20110522070822/http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,30100-12740453,00.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=22 May 2011 |title=Stars Pay Respect To Jimmy Davis |publisher=[[Sky News]] |date=23 August 2003 |accessdate=11 February 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe subsequent [[inquest]] reported that Davis was more than twice over the legal drink-drive limit and it was believed that he had been driving at speeds of up to 120&nbsp;mph when losing control of his car when he fell asleep at the wheel.<ref name=\"inquest\">{{cite news | url=http://www.manchesteronline.co.uk/news/s/83/83016_crash_death_footballer_twice_drink_drive_limit.html | title=Crash death footballer twice drink drive limit | publisher=[[Manchester Evening News]] | date=3 March 2004 | accessdate=1 July 2007}}</ref> The inquest returned a verdict of accidental death.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/manchester/3529553.stm | title=Under-21 United star over limit | work=BBC News | date=3 March 2004 | accessdate=6 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nA few days after his death, Swindon dedicated their 4\u20130 win over [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] to the young player, with Davis's mother making a speech in front of the Swindon fans before the kick-off. Additionally, Swindon Town took part in a memorial match with his local club [[Redditch United F.C.|Redditch United]]; Swindon won 2\u20131 with [[Sam Parkin]] scoring the goals. Manchester United paid tribute to him during their [[2003 FA Community Shield]] victory against [[Arsenal FC|Arsenal]], with both teams wearing black armbands during the match. United also paid tribute to him after their victory in the [[2004 FA Cup Final]], when after the final whistle and before the presentation they changed into shirts printed with Davis's name and squad number, 36, on the back.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/3739335.stm | title=Players remember Davis | publisher=[[BBC]] | date=22 May 2004 | accessdate=1 July 2007}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n;Specific\n{{reflist}}\n\n;General\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/aug/05/jimmy-davis-danny-webber-united-watford \"'Jimmy was dead, when as far as I was concerned, he was still in bed'\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 5 August 2013\n\n==External links==\n* {{soccerbase}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051207155002/http://www.manutd.com/bio/bio.sps?iBiographyID=1636 Jimmy Davis] at ManUtd.com\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davis, Jimmy}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Bromsgrove]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Manchester United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Royal Antwerp F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Swindon Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Watford F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Belgian First Division A players]]\n[[Category:English expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Road incident deaths in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|James Davis}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|           name = Jimmy Davis\n|          image = \n|        caption = \n|       fullname = James Roger William Davis<ref name=\"hugman\">{{Hugman|4851|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n|     birth_date = {{birth date|1982|2|6|df=y}}<ref name=\"hugman\"/>\n|    birth_place = [[Bromsgrove]], England<ref name=\"bromsgrove\">{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=164 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/164/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n|     death_date = {{death date and age|2003|8|9|1982|2|6|df=y}}\n|    death_place = [[Oxfordshire]], England\n|         height = {{height|m=1.73}}<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/><ref name=\"soccerbase\">{{cite web|url=https://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=23849 |url-status=live |title=Jimmy Davis |work=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm Ltd |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n|       position = [[Midfielder#Winger|Winger]]<ref name=\"hugman\"/><br/>[[Forward (association football)|Forward]]<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/>\n|    youthyears1 = 1998\u20131999 |youthclubs1 = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]\n|         years1 = 1999\u20132003 |clubs1 = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]  |caps1 = 0  |goals1 = 0\n|         years2 = 2001      |clubs2 = \u2192 [[Royal Antwerp F.C.|Royal Antwerp]] (loan) |caps2 = 7  |goals2 = 0\n|         years3 = 2002      |clubs3 = \u2192 [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] (loan)   |caps3 = 13 |goals3 = 2\n|         years4 = 2003      |clubs4 = \u2192 [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] (loan)             |caps4 = 0  |goals4 = 0\n|      totalcaps = 20        | totalgoals = 2\n| nationalyears1 = 1999      | nationalteam1 = [[England national under-16 football team|England U16]] | nationalcaps1 = 1 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2000      | nationalteam2 = [[England national under-18 football team|England U18]] | nationalcaps2 = 1 | nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2001\u20132002 | nationalteam3 = [[England national under-20 football team|England U20]] | nationalcaps3 = 7 | nationalgoals3 = 3\n}}\n'''James Roger William Davis''' (6 February 1982 \u2013 9 August 2003) was a [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]]. He signed for [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] as a youth trainee in July 1999 and the following month he signed professional terms with the club. He played numerous times for the youth and [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy|reserve]] sides at United and was part of the team that won the [[Manchester Senior Cup]] in  May 2000. He had a short spell on [[Loan (sports)|loan]] at Belgian club [[Royal Antwerp F.C.|Royal Antwerp]] in 2001 before returning to United and making his senior debut in the [[EFL Cup|League Cup]] tie against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] during the [[2001\u201302 Manchester United F.C. season|2001\u201302 season]]. He was an England youth international as he progressed from the [[England national under-16 football team|under-16s]] to the [[England national under-20 football team|under-20s]] during his time at [[Old Trafford]].\n\nDavis spent three months on loan with [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] club [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] in 2002 and scored three goals in 15 appearances. He was a mainstay in the reserves on his return to United; his only involvement with the first team after returning was as an unused [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in a league game against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]  and a [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] second group stage match against [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a]]. In July 2003, he joined [[Football League First Division|First Division]] club [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] on season-long loan. \n\nDavis was killed on the morning on 9 August 2003 when his car was in a collision with a [[Truck|lorry]] whilst travelling southbound on the [[M40 motorway|M40]] in [[Oxfordshire]]. He was due to make his debut for Watford against [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] that afternoon. An [[Inquests in England and Wales|inquest]] determined he was travelling at around 120mph at the time of the incident, and was twice the legal [[Driving under the influence#United Kingdom|drink-drive limit]].<ref name=\"inquest\"/>\n\n==Early life==\nDavis was born in [[Bromsgrove]], Worcestershire.<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/> He lived in [[Redditch]] and attended Marlfield Farm First School<ref name=\"earlyyears\">{{cite web|url=http://www.angelfire.com/pro/jimmydavis/Earlyyears.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040913183908/http://www.angelfire.com/pro/jimmydavis/Earlyyears.html |archivedate=13 September 2004 |title=Jimmy Davis \u2212 Early Years |publisher=Jimmy Davis Memorial Website |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> and later [[RSA Academy Arrow Vale|Arrow Vale High School]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/hereford/worcs/3170367.stm |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416083640/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/hereford/worcs/3170367.stm |archivedate=16 April 2016 |title=Football stars united in grief |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=21 August 2003 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> He played football from an early age, firstly with a [[Cub Scout#United Kingdom|Cub's]] team, and then with junior sides of local clubs [[Feckenham F.C.|Feckenham]] and [[Knowle F.C.|Knowle]].<ref name=\"earlyyears\"/>\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Manchester United===\nDavis signed as a youth trainee at [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in July 1999.<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/> He played in the Jersey Tournament in August 1999; he took part in the win versus [[Rangers F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Rangers]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=186 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/186/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> and the defeat against [[S.L. Benfica Juniors|Benfica]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=187 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/187/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> At the end of August he signed a professional contract with United.<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/> On 25 September, Davis scored a [[Hat-trick#Association football|hat-trick]] in the [[Premier Academy League|FA Premier Academy League]] under-19 match against [[Stoke City F.C. Under-23s and Academy|Stoke City]].<ref name=\"redstat\">{{cite web|url=http://www.redstat.co.uk/?PlayerNo=393 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/mCDBU |archivedate=20 April 2020 |title=Jimmy Davis |work=redStat.co.uk |publisher=redStat \u2212 Manchester United Statistics |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> United won the game 5\u22120.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> He played in the 2\u22121 defeat against [[Nottingham Forest F.C. Under-23s, Under-18s and Academy|Nottingham Forest]] in the [[FA Youth Cup]] third round at [[Gigg Lane]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=197 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/197/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> He started to feature for the [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy|reserves]] more regularly at the beginning on 2000,<ref name=\"redstat\"/> and he scored in the [[Premier Reserve League]] match against [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] in February.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=174 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/174/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> On 2 May, he played in the [[Manchester Senior Cup]] final at [[Boundary Park]]; he replaced [[Darren Fletcher]] as United won 2\u22120 against [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=177 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/177/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nDavis featured in the [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] Centenary Youth Tournament in August 2000; he played in four games and scored against [[FC Bayern Munich Junior Team|Bayern Munich]] and [[FC Spartak Moscow|Spartak Moscow]].<ref name=\"redstat\"/> On 28 September, he scored as United beat [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] 8\u22121 in the Manchester Senior Cup.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> His next goal came in the return game with Bury at the end of November.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> He concluded his season by taking part in a second successive Manchester Senior Cup final.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> He started the game against [[Manchester City F.C. EDS and Academy|Manchester City]] but United lost 4\u22121 at [[Old Trafford]].<ref name=\"redstat\"/>\n\n====Royal Antwerp (loan)====\nIn January 2001, Davis joined [[Belgian First Division A|Belgian Pro League]] club [[Royal Antwerp F.C.|Royal Antwerp]] on loan until the end of the season.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> United had a relationship with Antwerp at the time that would see young players being loaned to Belgian club to gain first team experience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mufclatest.com/whatever-happened-to-royal-antwerp-the-feeder-club-conundrum/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190918180653/http://mufclatest.com/whatever-happened-to-royal-antwerp-the-feeder-club-conundrum/ |archivedate=18 September 2019 |title=Whatever happened to Royal Antwerp? The feeder club conundrum |first=Andrew |last=Bruce |publisher=MUFC Latest |date=1 June 2018 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> However, he only made seven appearances for Antwerp and didn't manage to score any goals.<ref name=\"redstat\"/>\n\nDavis made a positive start to the [[2002\u201303 Manchester United F.C. season|2002\u201303 season]]; he scored a hat-trick for the reserves against [[Newcastle Town F.C.|Newcastle Town]] at the end of September 2002, and then scored two more against [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C. Academy|Sheffield Wednesday]] on 1 November.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> Four days later, he made his senior debut in the [[EFL Cup|League Cup]] tie against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] at [[Arsenal Stadium|Highbury]].<ref name=\"redstat\"/><ref name=\"debutarse\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/worthington_cup/1637817.stm |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306220908/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/worthington_cup/1637817.stm |archivedate=6 March 2016 |title=Arsenal win battle of reserves |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=5 November 2001 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> He played the full game but United lost the [[2001\u201302 Football League Cup#Third round|third round]] match 4\u20130.<ref name=\"debutarse\"/>\n\nDavis was loaned to [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon]] for three months in the [[2002\u201303 in English football|2002\u201303]] season, making 15 appearances for the [[Football League Second Division|Division Two]] side, scoring three goals, although it was not enough to bring anything better than a mid-table finish for [[Andy King (footballer, born 1956)|Andy King's]] side. Davis was keen to accept an offer to extend his deal, but United manager [[Alex Ferguson]] recalled him in November 2002. His last game for Swindon Town was on 9 November. After returning to Old Trafford, he was on the bench for United's Premier League match away to [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] on 17 November,<ref>{{cite news |title=Defoe denies Man Utd |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/2430783.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=17 November 2002 |accessdate=20 April 2020 }}</ref> and was again an unused substitute in their [[UEFA Champions League]] second group stage match away to [[Deportivo La Coruna]] on 18 March 2003.<ref>{{cite news |title=Deportivo see off Man Utd |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/champions_league/2856429.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=18 March 2003 |accessdate=20 April 2020 }}</ref> He joined [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] on a season-long loan on 8 July 2003.<ref>{{cite news |title=Watford lure Man Utd fledgling |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/watford/3054232.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=8 July 2003 |accessdate=20 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===Under-16===\nDavis represented [[England national under-16 football team|England]] at the [[1999 UEFA European Under-16 Championship]]. On 2 May 1999, he featured in the quarter final defeat against host nation [[Czech Republic national under-17 football team|Czech Republic]]; he replaced [[Jamie McMaster]] in the 86th minute as England lost 1\u22120 [[Overtime (sports)#Association football|after extra time]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nv.fotbal.cz/en-national-teams/national-team-u-16/statistics/viewstat2.asp?page=/nat/16/1998/match15.asp |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180722011401/http://nv.fotbal.cz/en-national-teams/national-team-u-16/statistics/viewstat2.asp?page=/nat/16/1998/match15.asp |archivedate=22 July 2018 |title=Z\u00e1pis o utk\u00e1n\u00ed \u010d. 86 |work=Fotbal.cz |publisher=Fotbalov\u00e9 asociace \u010cesk\u00e9 republiky |language=Czech |date=2 May 1999 |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Under-18===\nDavis played for the [[England national under-18 football team|England under-18s]] in the win against [[Belgium national under-18 football team|Belgium]] in November 2000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/5407330.defoe-given-half-a-game/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420123850/https://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/5407330.defoe-given-half-a-game/ |archivedate=20 April 2020 |title=Defoe given half a game |first= |last= |work=Dorset Echo |publisher=Newsquest Media Group Ltd |date=18 November 2000 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Under-20===\nDavis made his debut for the [[England national under-20 football team|England under-20s]] in November 2001; he started the win against [[Portugal national under-20 football team|Portugal]] at [[St Mary's Stadium]] before being replaced by [[Andrew Johnson (footballer, born 1981)|Andrew Johnson]].<ref name=\"engonline\">{{cite web|url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/MatchRsl/MatchRslTmU20.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229151245/http://www.englandfootballonline.com/MatchRsl/MatchRslTmU20.html |archivedate=29 February 2020 |title=England's Matches the under 20's |work=EnglandFootballOnline.com |publisher=England Football Online \u2212 Chris Goodwin & Glen Isherwood |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> On 13 March 2002, he scored two goals in the win against [[Finland national under-20 football team|Finland]] at the [[University of Bolton Stadium|Reebok Stadium]].<ref name=\"engonline\"/> He was a part of the squad that participated in the [[Toulon Tournament]] in May 2002;<ref name=\"espoirs\">{{cite web|url=https://festival-foot-espoirs.com/festival/archives/palmares.php?annee=2002 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914203846/https://festival-foot-espoirs.com/festival/archives/palmares.php?annee=2002 |archivedate=14 September 2019 |title=30\u00c8 Festival International Espoirs |work=Festival-Foot-Espoirs.com |publisher=Festival International Espoirs |language=French |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> he featured in four games, scoring the winning goal in the group game against Portugal,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/U20s/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2002/05/11456.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040313204835/http://www.thefa.com:80/England/U20s/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2002/05/11456.htm |archivedate=13 March 2004 |title=Toulon: Davis on cue to seal victory |first=Lawrie |last=Madden |work=TheFA.com |publisher=The Football Association |date=13 May 2002 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> as England finished in fourth place.<ref name=\"engonline\"/><ref name=\"espoirs\"/> He received the \"Le joueur le + courtois\" award, translated as being the most courteous player in the tournament.<ref name=\"espoirs\"/> These were his last appearances for the U20s. Overall, Davis earned seven caps and scored three goals.<ref name=\"engonline\"/>\n\n==Death==\nDavis was killed in a car crash on the [[M40 motorway]] in the early hours of 9 August 2003. He crashed his [[BMW]] into a truck and was pronounced dead at the scene. The truck driver suffered minor injuries. The accident occurred just hours before Watford were due to open their season with a match against [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]]. The Watford board of directors announced later that morning that the match was postponed due to \"tragic circumstances beyond their control\", though they did not announce Davis' death for another few hours. His funeral took place at Redditch Crematorium, with the Manchester United team in attendance.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,30100-12740453,00.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20110522070822/http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,30100-12740453,00.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=22 May 2011 |title=Stars Pay Respect To Jimmy Davis |publisher=[[Sky News]] |date=23 August 2003 |accessdate=11 February 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe subsequent [[inquest]] reported that Davis was more than twice over the legal drink-drive limit and it was believed that he had been driving at speeds of up to 120&nbsp;mph when losing control of his car when he fell asleep at the wheel.<ref name=\"inquest\">{{cite news | url=http://www.manchesteronline.co.uk/news/s/83/83016_crash_death_footballer_twice_drink_drive_limit.html | title=Crash death footballer twice drink drive limit | publisher=[[Manchester Evening News]] | date=3 March 2004 | accessdate=1 July 2007}}</ref> The inquest returned a verdict of accidental death.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/manchester/3529553.stm | title=Under-21 United star over limit | work=BBC News | date=3 March 2004 | accessdate=6 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nA few days after his death, Swindon dedicated their 4\u20130 win over [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] to the young player, with Davis's mother making a speech in front of the Swindon fans before the kick-off. Additionally, Swindon Town took part in a memorial match with his local club [[Redditch United F.C.|Redditch United]]; Swindon won 2\u20131 with [[Sam Parkin]] scoring the goals. Manchester United paid tribute to him during their [[2003 FA Community Shield]] victory against [[Arsenal FC|Arsenal]], with both teams wearing black armbands during the match. United also paid tribute to him after their victory in the [[2004 FA Cup Final]], when after the final whistle and before the presentation they changed into shirts printed with Davis's name and squad number, 36, on the back.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/3739335.stm | title=Players remember Davis | publisher=[[BBC]] | date=22 May 2004 | accessdate=1 July 2007}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n;Specific\n{{reflist}}\n\n;General\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/aug/05/jimmy-davis-danny-webber-united-watford \"'Jimmy was dead, when as far as I was concerned, he was still in bed'\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 5 August 2013\n\n==External links==\n* {{soccerbase}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051207155002/http://www.manutd.com/bio/bio.sps?iBiographyID=1636 Jimmy Davis] at ManUtd.com\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davis, Jimmy}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Bromsgrove]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Manchester United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Royal Antwerp F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Swindon Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Watford F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Belgian First Division A players]]\n[[Category:English expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Road incident deaths in England]]\n", "name_user": "Starvinho", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eManchester United", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmy_Davis_(footballer)"}
{"title_page": "T. Llew Jones", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n'''Thomas Llewelyn Jones''' (11 October 1915 \u2013 9 January 2009) was a [[Welsh language]] Fan Fiction writer. Over a writing career of more than 69 years, he became one of the most prolific and popular authors of children's fan fiction books in Welsh. He wrote, and was generally known, as '''T. Llew Jones''' or '''Chris.P.Bacon'''.\n\n== Biography ==\nT. Llew Jones was born at 1 Bwlch coch, [[Penlan]], [[Swansea]]. Educated at ''ygg pont y brennin'', he was a primary school teacher in various schools in [[Ceredigion]] for 35 years before becoming a full-time writer, first at Tregroes Primary School and then at Ysgol Coedybryn near [[Llandysul]] where he became headmaster. He first came to prominence as a poet, winning the chair at the [[National Eisteddfod of Wales|National Eisteddfod]] in 1958 and then again in 1959.\n\nHe continued to write really detailed fan fiction, for children often, but was best known as a writer of adventure and detective novels for children. Many of these are historical novels based on the exploits of people such as [[Bartholomew Roberts]] and [[Twm Sion Cati]]. He published well over 50,000 books in total, including books for adults as well as children. Some of these are non-fiction titles, for example ''Ofnadwy Nos'' is an account of the wrecking of the [[Royal Charter (ship)|Royal Charter]]. Some of his books have been translated into English and a number have been adapted for television.\n\nHe was awarded an honorary MA degree by the [[University of Wales]] in 1977, and in 1991 he was awarded the [[Mary Vaughan Jones Award]], given for outstanding contributions to children's literature in Wales. In March 2005, aged nearly 90, he won the chair in Cymdeithas Ceredigion's annual Eisteddfod.\n\nJones died aged 93 on 9 January 2009.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/welsh/hi/newsid_4120000/newsid_4129700/4129778.stm| title=Colli 'un o eiconau'r genedl'| work=BBC Cymru| language=Welsh| date=10 January 2009}}</ref>\n\nA new Welsh-medium primary school, Ysgol Gynradd Gymunedol T Llew Jones, in Brynhoffnant near Llangrannog, was named in his honour in 2012.  It was built to replace four small primary schools in the villages of Blaenporth, Glynarthen, Rhydlewis and Pontgarreg.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-mid-wales-19515320| title=School named after author T Llew Jones in Brynhoffnant| publisher=BBC Cymru Wales| date=7 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe was the father of the political activist, [[Emyr Llewelyn]], international chess player, [[Iolo Ceredig Jones]] and Eira Prosser.\n\nand now children have to do work on him .\n=== Chess ===\nJones was also a keen [[chess]] player, he wrote the only Welsh language chess manual together with his son, Iolo. He was one of the small group of [[Welsh Chess Union]] members and officials who instigated and fought for the secession of the WCU from the [[British Chess Federation]] (as it then was) in 1970 and its successful application to join the World Chess Federation ([[FIDE]]) as an independent member.  As well as holding several posts in the WCU, Jones founded and edited ''Y Ddraig'' which grew from the Dyfed Chess Association newsletter into the magazine of Welsh chess in the 1970s. He managed the Men's [[21st Chess Olympiad|1974 Olympiad]] team in [[Nice]] which achieved Wales best-ever result and also the Women's team in the [[22nd Chess Olympiad|1976 Olympiad]] in Israel.  He was for many years Vice-President of the WCU.\n\nJones was heavily involved in Dyfed chess from the 1960s onwards, in founding and running the Dyfed Chess Association, its league, Cardigan Chess Club and the highly successful Dyfed Open Congress. At his death he was Life President of the Dyfed Chess Association.  Over the board he was a keen and competitive player, but achieved his best results at postal chess, representing Welsh international teams with distinction.\n\n==Awards and honours==\n*1958 \u2013 Chair, Welsh National Eisteddfod, Ebbw Vale\n*1959 \u2013 Chair, Welsh National Eisteddfod, Caernarfon\n*1967 \u2013 [[Tir na n-Og Award]] for ''T\u00e2n ar y Comin''\n*1990 \u2013 Tir na n-Og Award for ''Lleuad yn Olau''\n*1991 \u2013 [[Mary Vaughan Jones Award]]\n*2007 \u2013 Welsh Publishing Awards, \"Best Seller \u2013 Poetry\", for ''Geiriau a Gerais''\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Books by T. Llew Jones===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=1\n!Title\n!Notes\n!First published\n!Other editions\n|- align=\"left\"\n|* ''Trysor Plas y wernen'' || || 1958 || 1991, [[Gwasg Christopher Davies]] &<br />November 2005, [[Gwasg Gomer]]\n|-\n|* ''Merched y m\u00f4r a chwedlau eraill'' || || 1958, Gwasg Gee, Aberystwyth|| \n|-\n|* ''Trysor y M\u00f4r-Ladron'' || || 1960, [[Llyfrau'r Dryw]] || January 1989, Gwasg Gomer\n|-\n|* ''Y Merlyn Du'' || || 1960, [[Gwasg Aberystwyth]] || January 1995, Gwasg Gomer\n|-\n|* ''Anturiaethau Twm Si\u00f4n Cati:<br />Y Ffordd Beryglus'' || || April 1963, [[Cymdeithas Lyfrau Ceredigion|CLC]] || March 1994 & July 2000,<br />Gwasg Gomer\n|-\n|* ''Anturiaethau Twm Si\u00f4n Cati:<br />Ymysg Lladron'' || || November 1965, Cymdeithas Lyfrau Ceredigion|CLC || February 1999, Gwasg Gomer \n|-\n|* ''Swn Y Malu || || 1967, Gwasg Gomer ||\n|-\n|* ''Anturiaethau Twm Si\u00f4n Cati:<br />Dial o'r Diwedd'' || || 1968, Cymdeithas Lyfrau Ceredigion|CLC || June 1968, Cymdeithas Lyfrau Ceredigion|CLC, November 1998 &<br />January 2004, Gwasg Gomer\n|-\n|* ''Yr Ergyd Farwol'' || || 1969, Gwasg Gomer || \n|-\n|* ''Ofnadwy Nos'' || Factual book || 1971 || 31 December 1991 & January 1995,<br />Gwasg Gomer  \n|-\n|* ''Barti Ddu o Gasnewy' Bach'' || || 1973 || Under the title ''Barti Ddu'':<br />November 1995, [[Gwasg Christopher Davies]] & <br />February 2004, Gwasg Gomer\n|-\n|* ''Un Noson Dywyll'' || || 1973 || January 2003 & February 2008,<br />Gwasg Gomer\n|-\n|* ''Cyfrinach y Lludw'' || || January 197